  "prompt": "How are polar covalent bonds formed?",
  "response": "Polar covalent bonds are formed when two atoms share electrons unequally due to a difference in their electronegativities. Electronegativity is the tendency of an atom to attract electrons toward itself when bonded to another atom. \n\nHere's how the formation of a polar covalent bond works:\n\n1. **Two Atoms**: A polar covalent bond typically occurs between two nonmetals. For example, in a molecule like water (H\u2082O), hydrogen (H) and oxygen (O) are the two atoms involved.\n\n2. **Difference in Electronegativity**: When the two atoms have differing electronegativities, the atom with the higher electronegativity will attract the shared electrons more strongly than the atom with the lower electronegativity. In the case of water, oxygen is more electronegative than hydrogen.\n\n3. **Unequal Sharing of Electrons**: Because of this difference, the shared electrons spend more time closer to the more electronegative atom (oxygen, in this case). This creates a slight negative charge (\u03b4-) at the oxygen end and a slight positive charge (\u03b4+) at the hydrogen end.\n\n4. **Resulting Dipole**: The unequal sharing of electrons results in a polar bond, characterized by a dipole moment. A dipole moment is a measure of the separation of positive and negative charges within the bond, creating polarity.\n\nIn summary, polar covalent bonds are formed when atoms with significantly different electronegativities share electrons unevenly, resulting in partial positive and negative charges and creating a dipole moment in the molecule.",
